{{Infobox LDS biography | name = Chi Hong (Sam) Wong | image = | caption = | alt = | birth_name = Chi Hong Wong | birth_date = 25 May 1962 | birth_place = [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] | spouse = Carol Lu | children = 4 | portals = LDS | position_or_quorum1 = [[First Quorum of the Seventy]] | called_by1 = [[Thomas S. Monson]] | start_date1 = {{start date|df=yes|2014|04|05}} – }}'''Chi Hong (Sam) Wong''' (born 25 May 1962) has been a [[general authority]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) since April 2014. He is a member of the [[First Quorum of the Seventy]].
Wong was born in [[British Hong Kong]] to Ngan Kan and Fat Wong. His future wife, Carol Lu, introduced him to the LDS Church and he became a member in 1982. In 1983, Wong married Lu and they moved to [[Oahu]], where Wong attended [[Brigham Young University–Hawaii]] and obtained degrees in accounting and computer science.
The Wongs then returned to Hong Kong, where he founded a business and quality consulting company. He later received an [[MBA]] from the [[Open University of Hong Kong]].
In the LDS Church, Wong has also served as a [[bishop (Latter Day Saints)|bishop]], [[stake president]] and [[area seventy]]. He became a general authority during the church's April 2014 [[general conference (LDS Church)|general conference]]. Since August 2014, he has served as a counselor in the presidency of the church's Asia [[Area (LDS Church)|Area]].<ref name="August 2015 changes">[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865627718/Area-leadership-assignments-announced.html?pg=all "LDS First Presidency announces area leadership assignments"], ''[[Church News]]'', 2 May 2015.</ref>
In the October 2014 general conference, Wong delivered a sermon in [[Cantonese]], becoming the first speaker to give a general conference address in a language other than English. Prior to the conference, the LDS Church had announced a new policy of allowing conference speakers to give addresses in their native languages.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/58487825-78/missionaries-church-lds-wong.html.csp |title= Mormon leader speaks in Cantonese — translation: history |newspaper= [[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |date= October 4, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |first= Tad |last= Walch |date= October 4, 2014 |title= Cantonese-speaking Saints thrilled by historic LDS conference talk in their language |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865612420/Cantonese-speaking-Saints-thrilled-by-historic-LDS-conference-talk-in-their-language.html?pg=all |newspaper= [[Deseret News]] }}</ref><ref>{{citation |first= Tad |last= Walch |date= October 5, 2014 |title= Global LDS diversity, growth on display at general conference |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865612461/Global-LDS-diversity-growth-on-display-at-general-conference.html |newspaper= Deseret News }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title= Several Native Languages Spoken in General Conference |url= http://ldsliving.com/story/77024-several-native-languages-spoken-in-general-conference |journal= [[LDS Living]] |date= October 6, 2014}}</ref>
