{{Infobox person | name = Shorpy Higginbotham | birth_name = Henry Sharpe Higginbotham | birth_date = November 23, 1986 | birth_place = Jefferson County, Alabama | death_date = January 25, 1928 | nationality = American | occupation = Coal mine laborer }}
Henry Sharpe Higginbotham, better known as '''Shorpy Higginbotham''' ( November 23, 1896 — January 25, 1928)<ref name="Shorpy"/> was a [[laborer]] in an [[Alabama]] [[coal mine]] in the early twentieth century. He served in [[World War I]] before returning to the mines, where he was killed by a falling rock in 1928.<ref name="Shorpy"/> Higginbotham was the subject of a series of photographs by [[Lewis Hine]] that showed him as a boy working in the dangerous environment of a coal mine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Manning|first=Joe|title=Henry Sharp Higginbotham|url=http://www.morningsonmaplestreet.com/index.html|publisher=Mornings on Maple Street|accessdate=25 December 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217001047/http://www.morningsonmaplestreet.com/index.html|archivedate=17 February 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name="Flynt1989">{{cite book|author=Wayne Flynt|title=Poor But Proud: Alabama's Poor Whites|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxEoAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=University of Alabama Press|isbn=978-0-8173-0424-9|page=125}}</ref> He is the namesake of the historical photography blog [[Shorpy.com]], where he has become a symbol of [[child labor]] in the United States.<ref name="Shorpy">{{cite web|author=Dave|title=Shorpy Higginbotham|url=http://www.shorpy.com/shorpy|publisher=[[Shorpy.com]]|accessdate=25 December 2012 }}</ref>
